            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What are the duties of a project manager?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A project manager carries out several duties and they are:</p><ol><li>Initiates a project plan and carries it out, works out its designs, executes, monitors, controls and closes it. </li><li>Leads and directs the project from the beginning to the end. </li><li>Works out strategies before other team members play one role or the other. </li></ol><p>This is why many people adduce the success or failure of any project to the project manager. Several industries like construction, architecture, petrochemical, information technology and other firms involved in the production of products and professional services employ this job title.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Do you need a degree to be a project manager?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>You do not need a degree to become a project manager. A Diploma in Building and Construction (Management) with extensive experience in the construction industry, for instance, qualifies you to become a project manager without a degree in the construction space.</p><p>However, it becomes necessary to own a degree if you are planning to manage and direct complex projects and lead teams. You can then earn a bachelor’s or master’s degree or a professional certificate.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is Project Manager Certification?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>Project manager certification is the certificate that empowers a project manager to function successfully in that capacity. The globally recognized certification that is the gold standard for professionals in this space is known as the PMP certification.</p><p>To become certified as a PMP professional, follow the five steps below:</p><ol><li>ensure your eligibility to become a certified project manager</li><li>read the PMP credentials book</li><li>become a local member of the professional body </li><li>get registered for the PMP examination </li><li>study the PMBOK® Guide.</li><li>Pass the certification exam.</li></ol><p>Following the steps listed above, will help you become a certified project manager.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How do I become a certified project manager?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>To become a certified project manager, follow the steps below: </p><ol><li>You need a bachelor’s degree, 4500 hours of project management experience, and 35 hours of&nbsp; training or a secondary degree, 7500 hours of experience, and 35 hours of training</li><li>Become a member of PMI </li><li>Pay the PMP examination fees </li><li>Schedule the PMP exam and study </li><li>Take the PMP exam and pass</li></ol>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Do certified project managers get paid well?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>Yes, depending on the location, work experience, and financial capacity of the company among other parameters. Project managers are paid $134k in Australia, $133k in Switzerland, and $108k in the United States. In China, they’re paid $24k while in India they’re paid $27k.</p><p>These vary based on prevailing factors from one location to another and the company in question. For instance, while the average pay is $108k in the US, some states pay different salaries for different categories of project managers.</p><p>Experienced and established professionals are paid $96k while those with little or no experience (often known as entry levels) earn $89k.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How long does it take to become a certified project manager?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>There is no fixed time required to become a certified project manager. It solely depends on your abilities. Keep in mind that there are time-based procedures you must undertake, such as:</p><ol><li>A secondary degree and 7,500 hours of leading and directing projects </li><li>35 hours of project management education </li></ol><p>OR</p><ol><li>Four-year degree and 4,500 hours of leading and directing projects </li><li>35 hours of project management education. </li></ol><p>AND</p><ol><li>3-4 months to prepare for the exam.</li></ol>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much do PMP certified project managers make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>The average annual income of a PMP certified project manager is $90,033. The lowest salary in this category is $59k while the highest-paid earns $134k in the US. There may also be extra payments and cash rewards aside from the salary, such as a bonus, profit sharing, and compensations.</p><p>In 2017, a certified PMP Project manager earned nothing less than $83k as an average salary annually. There is a remarkable difference between PMP certified project managers’ salary and that of non-certified project managers. A certified PMP earns at least 20% more than those who are not certified.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much does a project manager make an hour?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A project manager makes $63 per hour on average in the United States. However, it ranges between $56 to $71, and depends on your level of experience, certifications, skills, education, and location. For instance, as a certified project manager, you can earn 23% more than those who are not certified.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much do entry level project managers make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>The salary of entry-level project managers is $75,596 in the United States. Experienced project managers earn $96.425.An entry level project manager’s job is great for people who are just starting out. It will help them gain the necessary skills and expertise they need in the field and build their career.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much does a Senior project manager make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>The average salary for a senior project manager is $113,735 per year in the United States. Nationally it varies from $52,000 to $173,000.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What does an IT project manager do?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>IT project managers take care of the information technology plan from the initiation, design, and implementation right through to the closure. </p><ul><li>They ensure that processes are on track from the start of an IT project to the end. </li><li>They make sure IT projects are completed according to plan, budget, and deadline. </li><li>They consult with clients and vendors to make sure everyone is on the same page. </li><li>They plan schedules and assign tasks to team members and ensure they work towards completing the project successfully.</li></ul>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is a Contracts Manager’s role?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A contracts manager performs the following roles in any company: </p><ol><li>Plans projects </li><li>Promotes HS&amp;E(Health, Safety, and Environment) concerns </li><li>Ensures quality service </li><li>Maintains good customer relationships. </li><li>Is in charge of result-oriented program planning that the team members can follow with no hitch so that they work in accordance with the rules of the company. </li><li>Procures all the materials needed for the successful execution of the project. </li><li>Leads by example by promoting health, safety and the environment. </li><li>Ensures site workers comply with the HS&amp;E of the company regulations by providing training to other team members where and when necessary.</li></ol>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How long does it take to become a construction manager?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>It will take between 4 to 6 years to become a construction manager. You need to have either a bachelor’s degree, a master’s degree, or an associate degree. The degree can be in construction management, construction science, architecture or engineering. Employers are looking to hire a construction manager who is well educated. You will need a considerable amount of work-related skill, knowledge or experience, on-the-job training or vocational training.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What does a junior project manager do?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A junior project manager offers assistance in managing projects by giving out pieces of advice related to project management to organizations/companies in need of professional service. From the term junior, it is evident that they work directly under the supervision of a higher manager known as the senior project manager, as an assistant.</p><p>Junior project manager is a designation offered in software development firms, engineering industries, and other organizations in need of project managerial services. A junior project manager performs different duties such as:</p><ol><li>assisting the senior project manager</li><li>creating project plans</li><li>monitoring the progress of given projects and </li><li>reporting project results.</li></ol>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is an assistant project manager’s role?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>An assistant project manager is charged with the responsibility of assisting project managers in the course of executing project-related activities such as: </p><ol><li>Generating invoices for clients as directed by the project manager and according to the services carried out. </li><li>Ensuring smooth communication with clients regarding intended projects and their objectives. </li><li>Answering clients queries regarding the project </li><li>Giving the project manager necessary feedback. </li><li>Working hand in hand with all project managers to ensure the achievement of project goals.</li></ol>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much do junior project managers make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>Junior project managers make up to $70,000 a year in the United States. This is based on their average salary. A new junior project manager can make a starting salary of around $52,500 and this increases as he gains more experience.</p><p>How much a junior project manager will make varies from company to company, industry to industry, and also from one country to another. Junior project managers in the UK earn £29,114 a year on average. Construction companies pay $66, 136 on average while IT companies pay an average of $62,000.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much do freelance project managers make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>Freelance project managers make between $21,500 and $148,000 resulting in an average of $78,517 annually in the US. There is a growing awareness of freelance opportunities as there are about 12% of freelance project managers and 88% permanent project managers in the United States. Many people are embracing freelance opportunities to carve out time for other businesses. They take on freelance project managing jobs to enjoy benefits coming from different companies. The choice boils down to personal financial goals.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is a construction project manager’s job description?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A construction project manager’s job description is:</p><ol><li>To supervise building projects from inception to completion. </li><li>To employ laborers and negotiate contracts </li><li>To obtain all needed documents and other required permits before commencing a building project on any site. </li><li>To ensure all projects are completed within a given time frame and according to agreed budgets.</li></ol><p>Aside from having a bachelor’s degree and other related certification, a construction project manager is expected to have adequate work experience.</p>"
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much does a contract project manager make?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "<p>A contract project manager makes an average of $90,337 per year in the United States. Contract project managers are high in demand because companies need professionals who can come in for a period to manage one-off projects and then leave. As a contract manager, you can choose which projects to work on and you earn more money. Different contracts will also help you build up your experience in your career.</p>"
